title: Integrate `slog` and optimize processing
body:
This change:

* adds a `stderr` debug output (turned on by `-DD`) that prints statistics of different parts of the pipeline; this is based on `slog`
* Moves processing threads to be shared between different layers of writting stuff (data, vs index, vs index of an index and so on)

title: Use unwrap_or_default to simplfy code
body: Just a simple line cleanup. I just remembered it when I read the 1.16 rust announcement from the newsletter.

title: Added check if chunk exists on disk before processing further
body: This patches a regression that compresses and encrypts a chunk before determining if we need to write it to disk. We check if chunk exists once we determine the digest.

title: #15: refactor write pipeline
body: This prepares `rdedup` to pararelize just as described in #15

title: Auto rustfmt in vim
body:
Depends on https://github.com/dpc/rdedup/pull/81

I don't have strong opinion about the details. Eg I picked width = 80 because it's kind of a standard, and it's easy to read (at least for me).

title: config.yml: Use internal tags
body:
* Update `serde` and other deps
* Use `type` as tag for both encryption and chunking
* Rename enums to be uniform and self-documenting

title: Improve encryption config format
body:
* Change encryption config format to support no or different encryption
in the future.
* Fix sealed_key serialization

title: Added support for customizing the chunking algorithm bit size.
body:
Closes #40.

This MR adds support for custom bitsize settings for the bup chunking algorithm. The configuration is defined in a way to support more algorithms in the future.

What should the command line configuration be? I was thinking:
```rdedup init --chunking bup:17```

Or maybe:
```rdedup init --bup=17```

What do you think @dpc?

I will make additional commits once we determine the commandline arguments to use.

title: Force Rebuild of Clippy to match nightly build.
body: Clippy is closely linked to the version of nightly that it is running against so in order for our CI builds to be properly linted we need to always rebuild clippy.
